{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011zuQA1aCh7TTbBKtRTveXz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is clear now: there's an \"unclean shutdown\" being detected (\"Detected unclean shutdown - Lock file is not empty\"). This means the PVCs are NOT clean - they contain data from the first (crashed) attempt. Even though I deleted the PVCs and created new ones, the local-path provisioner is using the same underlying directory on the node - it seems the underlying storage wasn't actually cleaned up.\n\nThis is a known issue with `rancher.io/local-path` provisioner - it uses `hostPath` directories on the node, and when you delete a PVC, it might not immediately clean up the directory if the data directory is retained.\nI'm realizing the new PVCs might be reusing the same hostPath directory from before, so when mongod tries to start fresh, it finds the old lock file and crashes because the featureCompatibilityVersion document is missing from the partially-initialized data directory. So the pattern is clear: mongod starts during the scaling attempt, begins initialization but can't complete the featureCompatibilityVersion document in replica set mode, then gets killed by the liveness probe timeout around 210 seconds. On the next container restart, it detects the unclean shutdown and the incomplete state, creating a loop where it can't recover.\n\nThe core issue is that mongod in replica set mode needs to be added to the replica set to fully initialize, but the liveness probe kills it before that can happen—especially since keyFile authentication prevents even localhost connections until the replica set is properly configured.\n\nI successfully added replica-3 to the replica set initially, but when it crashes and restarts with empty state, it crashes again before it can rejoin. Let me trace through what's actually happening in this scaling attempt.\n\nLooking at the timeline more carefully: the pods started fresh, and I ran rs.add() for pods 3 and 4 around 4-5 minutes in. But the liveness probe was already killing them at the 210-second mark, which means they were crashing during their initial boot before they could even complete initial sync. Each restart left the data directory in a dirty state, so the next boot would fail again. The real problem is that mongod needs to complete its startup sequence and get added to the replica set before the liveness probe kills it, but the timing isn't working out. The liveness probe is killing mongod before it can complete initial sync and get the FCV document from the primary, so I need to either delay the probe long enough for sync to finish, or handle the missing FCV document differently—maybe by running a repair operation first if the data directory exists but is corrupted. The issue is that on a fresh node with no users, the liveness probe can't authenticate as `admin-user`, so it fails repeatedly and kills the container before initial sync completes. Looking back at the timeline, I added the replica set members around 2 minutes after the pods started, which was well before the liveness probe would have triggered at 3.5 minutes—so the timing should have worked, but something else went wrong.\n\nThe real problem is that when mongod restarts on a dirty data directory with partial replica set initialization but no FCV document, it gets stuck. Instead of fighting the liveness probe timing, I should create an entrypoint wrapper that automatically runs a repair operation to fix the FCV and let mongod start normally.\n\nThe simpler approach would be to scale down, delete the bad PVCs, then scale back up and add the members to the replica set within the liveness probe window. But the timing is tight—the liveness probe will kill the pod if authentication fails, which happens until initial sync completes. If the initial sync is fast enough on an mostly-empty replica set, auth should work and the liveness probe will pass. sync completes quickly, then the liveness probe should pass once authentication works. The key difference from my first attempt is timing—I need to add the new members to the replica set within 30-60 seconds of them starting, before the liveness probe gets too close to failing. Let me check if replica-3 and replica-4 are already in the replica set status.\n\nIt looks like rs.add() already succeeded for both members, but the pods are stuck in CrashLoopBackOff. Since the replica set configuration already includes them, once the pods restart cleanly they should automatically rejoin and begin initial sync. I need to fix the startup issue—either by wiping the data directory if mongod.lock exists or by running a repair operation on startup.\n\nOption 2 (running `mongod --repair` before the main start) seems cleanest, but I can't target specific pods in a StatefulSet. The better approach is to modify the startup command to check if repair is needed and run it automatically. When a fresh pod starts in replica set mode without existing data, MongoDB should initialize successfully in STARTUP2 state and wait for initial sync. The crash we're seeing with \"missing featureCompatibilityVersion document\" on a completely empty data directory suggests either leftover metadata files from a previous run or some other state persisting between restarts. I need to figure out why MongoDB thinks there's existing data when the directory should be clean. The collection data with 93 records confirms the local-path provisioner is reusing directories with leftover MongoDB data instead of cleaning them up between PVC deletions and recreations. I need to handle this dirty state, and the best approach is to add a `--repair` flag on startup to recover from the corrupted data.\n\nMy plan is to scale the StatefulSet back down to 3 replicas first (since pods 3 and 4 are stuck in CrashLoopBackOff), then add an init container or modify the startup command to run the repair before MongoDB starts normally. The replica set config on the primary already knows about members 3 and 4, so when those pods restart with clean data, mongod will start up cleanly, sync from the primary, and join the replica set automatically. My plan is to scale down to 3, use a temporary pod to repair or wipe the data directories on the PVCs for pods 3 and 4, then scale back up so they can start fresh.\n\nActually, running `--repair` is better than wiping because it fixes the FCV issue specifically without destroying data, and once mongod starts and joins the replica set, initial sync will replace everything with fresh data from the primary anyway. The real blocker is that mongod can't even start right now because of the FCV corruption.\n\nWhen `--repair` runs, it'll recover the WiredTiger database and restore the FCV document, then mongod can start normally. But I'm realizing there's a complication: the stale data might have an old replica set config stored in its local database that conflicts with the new RS membership I'm trying to add it to.\n\nThe simplest solution is to just wipe the data directory completely before starting mongod. Since these pods will do initial sync anyway and pull all their data from the primary, clearing `/data/db` is safe and correct. I could add an init container to the StatefulSet that clears the data directory before mongod starts, though I need to be careful about whether this runs on existing pods or just new ones.\n\nActually, wiping the data unconditionally would destroy the real data on pods 0, 1, and 2, which is a problem. I need a smarter approach. The cleanest option is to scale down to 3 pods, then create temporary pods that mount the PVCs for pods 3 and 4 specifically, wipe their data directories, and exit. This way I'm only touching the problematic pods without risking the existing data. Alternatively, I could try running `mongod --repair` via exec while those pods are in CrashLoopBackOff. Wiping the data might be simpler than running repair, but I 