{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01LnzDrtUuFEEUWUNDKFDgXR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The FCV error is STILL happening after wiping and restarting! This is very strange. \n\nLooking at the log, I can see:\n- `local.replset.oplogTruncateAfterPoint` - exists\n- `local.replset.minvalid` - exists\n- `local.replset.election` - exists\n- `local.startup_log` - exists\n\nThese are mongodb collections that should NOT exist in a truly clean empty directory. The wipe pod DID run (`rm -rf /data/db/*`), but apparently there's still data remaining.\nWait, maybe the wipe command didn't fully clear everything including dotfiles, or there's a permission issue preventing deletion. Or possibly the local-path provisioner is pointing to a different volume than what we cleared, and the directory got repopulated. Actually, looking at those minimal collections that exist—those are the bare minimum mongod creates when initializing.\n\nLooking at the WiredTiger catalog, I'm seeing only 4 collections when there should be more. The FCV document lives in `admin.system.version`, and it's missing along with the RS config and user collections. So the database is in an incomplete initialization state.\n\nWhat's happening is mongod starts fresh with a clean data directory, creates the basic local collections, then gets killed by the liveness probe before it can finish initialization and create the FCV document. When it restarts, it finds this partial state and fails because the FCV is missing.\n\nThe root cause is clear now: the wipe is working, but mongod gets terminated mid-initialization. I need to handle this incomplete state, and one approach is to run `mongod --repair` on each startup to clean up any partial initialization.\n\nThe `--repair` command rebuilds indexes, removes corrupt objects, and importantly, reconstructs the missing FCV document. The key question is whether `--repair` needs the replSetName config or if it can run standalone as a maintenance operation.\n\nI'm considering modifying the StatefulSet command to conditionally run repair before starting mongod, checking for a stale lock file first. However, this would trigger a rolling restart across all pods, which is risky even with a majority present. Another option is increasing the liveness probe's initial delay to give mongod more time to start up.\n\nThe cleanest approach would be using an init container that detects partial state and runs repair automatically, but that also requires modifying the StatefulSet. Alternatively, I could create a temporary pod that mounts the problematic PVCs directly and runs repair without touching the StatefulSet—this would fix the data directory's state so mongod starts normally on the next boot.\n\nBut I'm realizing the repair might need the keyFile too, and there's another issue: even after repair creates the FCV document, the pod will still start as an unconfigured replica set member. The primary will send it the config via heartbeat and trigger initial sync, but the liveness probe could kill it before that completes.\n\nThe real problem is that the liveness probe fails because auth isn't set up yet, so the pod gets killed and we're back to a dirty state. I need to either give mongod enough time to complete initial sync by increasing the liveness probe delay, or find a way to handle the RS initialization properly during startup.\n\nThe practical solution is to add a startup command that detects an unclean shutdown and runs repair before mongod starts normally. This way, when the StatefulSet rolls out with the updated spec, pods will restart cleanly without getting stuck in the auth failure loop.\n\nNow I'm checking whether a rolling restart is safe with the current cluster state—we have three working members with a primary, and the StatefulSet uses parallel pod management, which could restart all pods simultaneously.\n\nActually, for rolling updates the pods still restart one at a time from highest to lowest ordinal, so we'd restart pod 4, then 3, 2, 1, 0. The repair command should be a no-op for healthy pods since their lock files will be empty or missing, only triggering on pods with unclean shutdowns.\n\nDuring the rolling restart, when a secondary like pod 2 gets terminated, it's a clean shutdown so the lock file clears and no repair is needed. The real question is whether the primary gets restarted during this update—if it does, there'll be an election, but the cluster should handle it with 3 members currently healthy out of 5 total in the replica set config.\n\nActually, with 5 configured members and only 2 remaining after the primary goes down, they can't achieve the 3-vote majority needed for an election. This is a problem. The right approach is to ensure all 5 members are healthy before starting the rolling update, but pods 3 and 4 aren't coming up properly. So instead, I should create repair pods that mount the PVCs for 3 and 4 and run the repair command directly.\n\nOnce repair completes and I scale back to 5, the new pods should start with clean data. The primary will send the replica set config via heartbeat within 2 seconds, triggering initial sync. For a small dataset, initial sync should finish in under 30 seconds, well before the liveness probe would kill the pod.\n\nThe real constraint is that the liveness probe checks at 60 seconds, and by then the member should have synced and become SECONDARY, making the auth-based probe pass. The key is whether mongod starts quickly enough after repair and whether the primary's heartbeat reaches it immediately—both should happen automatically since the primary heartbeats every 2 seconds. So I need to run repair on those pods, but I'm concerned about whether `--repair` should be run with the replica set config or in standalone mode. The config file includes the keyFile requirement, but repair shouldn't need authentication. Let me think through whether running repair with the replSetName in the config will cause issues or if it'll just repair the data files without trying to connect to the replica set.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the real problem here: the wipe did work, but when mongod starts fresh in replica set mode, it creates the local collections but gets killed before it can create the FCV document. The issue isn't stale data—it's that a fresh start in RS mode gets interrupted before completing initialization. So I need to either let mongod finish creating the FCV document itself, or get it from initial sync.\n\nBut that's circular: mongod needs to be running to join the RS and sync the FCV, but it needs the FCV to run in the first place. Though MongoDB 6.0 should handle a completely empty data directory without requiring a pre-existing FCV document. The real issue is probably partial state—the wipe clears files but something's left behind that causes mongod to expect an FCV document that isn't there. got killed mid-initialization instead of from stale data. The fix is to add a repair step to the StatefulSet that runs conditionally based on detecting a non-empty lock file, which would indicate an interrupted startup from a previous SIGKILL by the liveness probe.\n\nI'm modifying the container command to use a shell wrapper that checks for the lock file and runs repair if needed before starting mongod normally. This way pods 0, 1, 2 with clean state skip the repair and start immediately, while pods 3 and 4 that were killed mid-initialization get repaired first.\n\nThe StatefulSet update will trigger a rolling update that processes pods one at a time from highest to lowest ordinal, with each pod waiting until the previous one is Running and Ready before proceeding.\n\nThe tricky part is the availability impact during this process: when the healthy members (pods 2, 1, 0) restart in sequence, we could temporarily drop below quorum if pod 1 is the primary and triggers an election while only two members are healthy. However, pods 3 and 4 are already stuck in CrashLoopBackOff, so the rolling update will hit them first (highest ordinals), and once they restart with the repair logic, they should recover and rejoin the replica set.\n\nBut wait—the rolling update won't move to the next pod until the current one is Running and Ready. Since pods 3 and 4 are in CrashLoopBackOff and not Ready, the update gets stuck waiting for them indefinitely. I need a different strategy here. Instead of relying on the rolling update to fix them, I should run a repair operation through a temporary pod first, then scale back up to let the healthy members update normally.\n\nFor the repair pod, I'd need to mount the same PVC, the mongo-keyfile secret, and the mongod-config configmap, then run the repair command and let it exit. The keyfile mount is important because mongod reads the config which references the keyFile path. But I'm wondering if `mongod --repair` will actually resolve the FCV issue on what's essentially an empty database with just replication metadata files.\n\nLooking at how MongoDB handles this—when `mongod --repair` runs, it rebuilds WiredTiger indexes and attempts recovery from invalid states. For the FCV problem specifically, if `admin.system.version` doesn't exist, MongoDB creates it with the appropriate FCV for that version. I'll try running the repair pods and see if that fixes it; worst case it doesn't work and I'll need a different approach.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3207,"cache_read_input_tokens":70503,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3207},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"936bc9c9-9092-403d-ab9a-8c86016c8439","uuid":"446da9fa-1d90-4f0a-955d-7b1346f7778e","request_id":"req_011Cc84j9eAU71uVUdfbvm5b"}
