{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017Dd3C1CkWS33UXymhYER4T","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I've patched the StatefulSet with a new command that:\n1. Checks if the lock file is non-empty (unclean shutdown)\n2. If so, runs `mongod --repair --dbpath /data/db`\n3. Then starts normally\n\nThis patch will trigger a rolling update of the StatefulSet. The rolling update goes from highest ordinal (4) to lowest (0). Since pods 3 and 4 are currently NOT running (scaled to 3), the rolling update needs to start pods 3 and 4 with the new config.\n\nWait, actually - the rolling update will only update pods that exist and are at the old revision. \n\nPods 3 and 4 don't exist yet, so when I scale back to 5, they'll be created with the new config automatically. Pods 0, 1, and 2 are at the old revision and will be updated one at a time through the rolling update. Since they had clean shutdowns, the auto-repair won't trigger on them. But restarting all three sequentially could impact availability, so I need to think about whether that's acceptable. So when pod 1 (the PRIMARY) restarts during the rolling update, the replica set drops to just 2 healthy members—pods 0 and 2—but still needs 3 votes out of the 5 configured members to elect a new primary. Since they only have 2 votes between them, no election can happen, and the cluster loses its primary until pod 1 comes back online. The good news is that pod 1 should restart quickly since it's just a config change with no data corruption involved. So if pod 1 goes down, we'd only have 2 votes available, which falls short of the 3-vote majority needed—meaning the replica set loses its primary and write availability, even if just temporarily. Since pod 1 should recover within 30-60 seconds, there's a brief window of unavailability. To avoid this entirely, I could temporarily remove the unhealthy members 3 and 4 from the replica set configuration, reducing t